generated class in a subdirectory under test resources. I wonder if I should use an inner class since there's no Java file. The rule says test class files should follow a one-to-one mapping, but I'm curious if helper classes might be allowed. It's tricky since I want to ensure adequate coverage while possibly using a non-Test file, but risks are involved with that approach. There's so much to consider!\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Analyzing class loading and registration**\\n\\nI'm wondering if using PathMatchingResourcePatternResolver with the app classloader could help search the JRT. It might find classes like java/time/*.class in the boot module, allowing me to use Class.forName(\\\"java.time.Clock\\\"). However, registering java.time classes as Spring beans could fail due to possible lack of a default constructor. I’m curious if annotatedReader.register could help with that, but the refresh process could still run into issues if a bean needs to be instantiated without a required constructor. It's quite complicated!\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_RtJYBdBeokT1xYwvsYqrPWhx|fc_0c10cbc4c9e09abd016a250457cd608190bde983260a08ad23", "name": "bash", "arguments": {"command": "find /home/vjovanov/c/forge/forge1/graalvm-reachability-metadata/forge/local_repositories/source_context/org.springframework.boot/spring-boot/4.0.6/main/extracted/org/springframework/boot -type d | sed 's|.*/extracted/||' | sort | head -100"}}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "oca/gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 1490, "output": 1112, "cacheRead": 25600, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 28202, "cost": {"input": 0, "output": 0, "cacheRead": 0, "cacheWrite": 0, "total": 0}}, "stopReason": "toolUse", "timestamp": 1780810814219, "responseId": "resp_0c10cbc4c9e09abd016a25043ea99481908fdc7245861ed152"}}
