 native image might include class metadata, which means ClassLoader.getResource for classpath classes could potentially work. However, I'm not entirely sure. There's the option to use SpringApplication.load directly on the JVM, but since the tests are also running natively, I want to prevent any failures. Maybe leveraging the defined package could help? For Class.forName to function, it seems I need the right resources, but in native, it should work for known library classes if the metadata is there.\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_JeAHwZtKaZvfnNQmpL7vrhZ9|fc_0c10cbc4c9e09abd016a25057b6250819094a9e29b7e38a3d2", "name": "bash", "arguments": {"command": "grep -R \"org.springframework.boot.admin\" -n /home/vjovanov/c/forge/forge1/graalvm-reachability-metadata/forge/local_repositories/source_context/org.springframework.boot/spring-boot/4.0.6/main/extracted | head -20; find /home/vjovanov/c/forge/forge1/graalvm-reachability-metadata/forge/local_repositories/source_context/org.springframework.boot/spring-boot/4.0.6/main/extracted -path '*META-INF*' -type f | head -50"}}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "oca/gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 616, "output": 863, "cacheRead": 37376, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 38855, "cost": {"input": 0, "output": 0, "cacheRead": 0, "cacheWrite": 0, "total": 0}}, "stopReason": "toolUse", "timestamp": 1780811113140, "responseId": "resp_0c10cbc4c9e09abd016a250569c4d48190936f9770dac236f1"}}
